text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

jon sharman
the independent

when one voice becomes many... #day29 for #100daysofcreativity challenge is here and is dedicated to all those who take a stand against all odds...i believe that it is much more powerful to speak up than to silently resent later. in fact it is one of the greatest freedoms one has, which can completely change any situation.

in words of audre lorde, "when i dare to be powerful, to use my strength in the service of my vision, then it becomes less and less important whether i am afraid." so don't be afraid. speak up, even if your voice shakes.

#repost @casiedanenhauer from my personal page because it so desperately falls into the category of sexual health.

men! i love you, but please hear me (and when i say me i mean all women) for the sake of all of us!

i’m allowed to be sexy and that’s not an invitation. i’m allowed to be well versed in sexual health and not want to see your dick pics. i’m allowed to know way more about genitals, foreplay, and the power of presence in sexuality than you and that doesn’t mean i’m easy. i’m allowed to want to kiss you and not want to have sex with you. i’m allowed to confidently express my sexuality and not choose you to express that with. i’m allowed to want to have sex and not be a slut. i’m allowed to say yes and later say no. i’m allowed to let you inside of me and request a conversation beforehand. i’m allowed to have boundaries and it’s ok if they change through communication.i allowed to be a successful professional and have a sexual identity. i’m allowed to want to snuggle and not have to keep repeating “no” to your advances. i’m allowed to directly communicate my needs and that have nothing to do with how manly you are. .
i’ve been reflecting a lot this week on my intimate experiences throughout my entire life. one of my earliest memories of sexual shaming was when one of the mothers of a  classmate spread the rumor that “casie was fast and easy” because she came to school one day and saw me sitting on my boyfriend’s lap. i was 9.  all the parents were concerned i was a slut because i was holding hands and cuddling with a boy. i feel a visceral reaction to that experience even today. the implications and complex emotions that arose from that experience are enough to give me pause when i think about how i’ve embraced my sexuality (or not) ever since. .
i was lucky to have a fairly sex positive mom and any conversation around that topic was answered in the most direct and accurate way possible. she encouraged me to talk with her when i started having sex in high school and i did. i somehow always had the passion for talking about all things sex and relationships related with my friends and i had the pleasure (continued below)...

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
tack vare #metoo kom det ju fram hur otäckt många som blivit sexuellt utnyttjade och ofredade redan som barn.

den här boken skulle jag önska att alla förskolor läste som en introduktion i ämnet. för att det är ju inte sagt att föräldrar läser den och speciellt inte de föräldrar som inte annars heller tänker på vikten av att lära barnen om de här frågorna.

bara den som vill av anna-carin magnusson handlar om liv som är ängslig eftersom johan ska hälsa på dem. han är en vuxen som alltid vill att hon ska sitta i hans knä och kramas. när hon säger att hon inte vill skojar han bara bort det. kompisen alice berättar att barn själva får bestämma om kramar och vem de ska vara nära. och det är det boken handlar om. de pratar om saken både på förskolan/i skolan (vilkendera liv går i kan tolkas fritt) och hemma med föräldrarna som inser att de gjort fel och börjar stå upp för livs kroppsliga integritet.

sexåringen som älskar ordlekar skrattade hejdlöst åt att piratälskande liv hörde att alice sade piratsaker istället för privatsaker. och åt när alice  tyckte att livs pappa själv skulle få sitta i johans knä om han nu tyckte det var så roligt. 
inte bara viktig, men också kul bok med andra ord! och bra när livs pedagog/lärare lär barnen hur de på någons miner och kroppsspråk kan försöka tyda om de vill kramas eller inte. här finns många möjligheter att jobba vidare med frågorna i förskolan eller skolan!

dessutom har karaktärerna olika hudfärger och en har hörapparat.

se kommentarerna för hur du kan vinna boken till valfritt dagis eller valfri skola i finland! 👍

text: fortsatte läsa på temat ”medelålders kropp” och det blev stina wolters ”kring denna kropp”, även denna självbiografisk. alla vet väl vem stina wolter är; antingen tänker man sven wolters dotter, konstnär, radiopratare eller kroppsaktivist på instagram eller kanske let’s dance. en mångsidig kvinna alltså. jag själv hade mest bilden av ”en galen kvinna dansande hemma i fula underkläder” i huvudet, och jag hade inte riktigt fattat varför hon gjorde det om jag ska vara ärlig. inte heller att folk blir så oerhört provocerade av att en stor kvinna tar plats. att kroppsaktivism och #metoo ska behövas 2018 är sorgligt, har vi inte kommit längre än så? ”kring denna kropp” är en alldeles fantastiskt vacker och gripande bok om stina och hennes relation till systern som dog i anorexia och till mamman, hennes relation till sig själv och till alla hon möter i livet, till hur hon bemöter människor. kroppen som ett problem finns där hela tiden, att passa in i mallen, att spela den kvinnoroll som förväntas. att vara överviktig är verkligen stigmatiserat och som smal funderar jag inte så mycket på det, inte behöver jag kämpa heller för att hålla vikten, jag bara är. jag läser en bok om mig själv, min bakgrund och meningen med allt och det är väl det som är stor litteratur, att väcka känslor och få läsaren att reflektera kring sitt liv. det är inte ofta jag gråter när jag läser men här kunde jag inte låta bli, det är så vackert och jag har mina egna sorger att komma över. tack stina ❤️

this is my heavy rotation tonight...and 'tis the season of all things "hurry up and get through the next five weeks" and all things grinch about the holidays. this is most definitely not the most wonderful time of the year for me, thanks to being a two-time childhood sexual abuse and childhood abandonment survivor. -
@iiswhoiis @christinaperri @kealasettle @pattimurin @caissielevy and @ladygaga : thank you, thank you, thank you. thank you for writing and/or singing such powerful songs and anthems as these. your voice and words in these days and times are so desperately needed and wanted! your songs speak the truth both bluntly and directly as to what any survivor of trauma experiences mentally, emotionally, and even physically. they attest to the rest of the world that one cannot simply "pick yourself up by the boot straps" or "let it (abc...xyz) go." again, thank you for being such a light of hope, inspiration, and for raising your hand to us survivors and saying "i get you and here's how!" please don't stop ringing out these messages of truth, help, and hope!!!
-
@ladygaga , could you please please please do a "christian" version of till it happens to you"? like with all of the christian-isms like "the lord won't give you more than you can handle" or "all things'll work together"? -
and @caissielevy and @pattimurin : when frozen goes on national tour, will you pretty pretty pretty please go on tour as anna and elsa?? because i live in nashville, tn and would seriously really love to see you two!!! #metoo #childhoodsexualabusesurvivor #childhoodtraumasurvivor #realtalk #tillithappenstoyou #innerchild #outerchild #nurturingparent #selfparenting #fightlikeagirl #thisisme #sorrynotsorryfortherealness

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
владимир познер: «я бы на месте брилева сдал свое британское гражданство. или российское»

евгения альбац: - владимир владимирович, спасибо вам большое. я очень благодарна вам за вашу позицию по #metoo, по женски, по вопросу о том, зачем и почему женщины борются за то, чтобы их нельзя было гладить по заднице тогда и там, где хочется… 
владимир познер: -т олько если им хочется. 
е. альбац: - совершенно верно. тогда можно договориться. у меня к вам вопрос по поводу последнего скандала с сергеем брилевым. 
мы с вами хорошо знаем, что в средствах массовой информации существует очень серьезное ограничение на участие иностранного капитала. так мы потеряли газету «ведомости», так мы потеряли стс, так мы потеряли целый ряд изданий. только 20% в капитале любого издания могут быть иностранно финансируемы. ни владелец, ни главный редактор, ни генеральный директор не может иметь никакого другого гражданства, кроме гражданства российской федерации. это запрещено российским законом. 
тут мы узнаем, что заместитель руководителя вгтрк… да, вы много раз говорили, что у вас гражданство соединенных штатов америки, франции, вы не являетесь руководителем, вам закон российский это позволяет. но тут мы узнаем, что человек, который является заместителем руководителя вгтрк и каждую неделю рассказывает российским гражданам, как им надо любить родину, что им надо думать об этой родине, и как хороша эта родина по сравнению с другими родинами и его в том числе, что этот человек оказывается давным-давно, сергей брилев, является гражданином великобритании, страны, с которой у нас, начиная с дела литвиненко, а именно с 2006 года, очень тяжелые, прямо скажем, отношения, имеет там собственность. и как он сам сообщил, это известно руководству российского государственного канала. я напомню, что это канал, который существует на деньги российских налогоплательщиков. никак иначе. 
вот у меня к вам вопрос: вы полагаете, это нормально, этично для заместителя руководителя вгтрк и одного из главных пропагандистов отечества иметь второе гражданство? спасибо. 
в. познер: - ах, евгения марковна, как же я люблю ваши вопросы!

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text_retweet: i used to order hard to find madonna records from his store from the back of magazines!!! #ripbleekerbob. this is a repost from legendary photographer #mickrock....“sad to hear of the passing of my old friend, #bleeckerbob. i hadn’t seen him in a number of years but in my early days in new york, he would often bring interesting characters who had floated into his store, to my studio on madison and 32nd. i remember the day he brought a very young #madonna by in 1980. she was totally unknown and at the time was primarily a dancer. the music came a little later. i took a few snaps of her, including this shot, which has become quite famous over the years. bob was one of the great hip new york city characters. a total one off, he will be sorely missed.” repost from @therealmickrock @madonna

for all of the people around the world whose familes have been torn apart or ended so that this inhuman bastard, his criminal family, and their cronies could live in luxury: rest in peril you no good fuck, good riddance.

george herbert walker bush was the prototype for the cheney vice presidency. where george w., the son, was cheney’s puppet, george the father was the puppeteer behind the reagan presidency. bush was a craven opportunist and was willing to casually break the law and subvert the constitution. his legacy as cia director, vice president, and eventually president is one of continued criminality. 
the following is only one of myriad examples: he orchestrated selling weapons to iran in their 1980s war against iraq, whom we were also arming, including with chemical weapons—old don rumsfeld was in on that one. then, he used the money to fund a group called the contras who planned to overthrow the sandinista government of nicauragua. this is important because the contra funding had already been taking place prior, but the us congress had deemed it illegal ordered the reagan administration to stop. so, to recap: he helped instigate a brutal war in asia, armed both sides, so that he could illegally fund one side of another war in central america intended to illegally topple an elected government. when i say “illegal” i mean internationally as well as domestically in these cases.

text:
from the #innerwoman in men to women⁣
⁣
dear women, sisters; from #sensitivity and #vulnerability, i express some of the #challenges we experience as men. it’s not your fault, it’s not ours, yet it’s in our hands to shift this and come together in a different way. ⁣
⁣
how tiring and frustrating it is to be initiating all the time facing rejection constantly with high levels of anxiety and uncertainty; exhausting to feel that we have to keep it all together, to feel the pressure and expectation that we need to outstand compared to other men, be unshakable, consistently provide and reflect a state of stability and groundedness (food, shelter, money, etc.)⁣
⁣
women, i know that this comes from conditioning. your mother, your mother's mother and who knows how long down the lineage in your family. neither you or us have been tought differently. and we’re walking a pathless path in healing our collective field of interaction and connection.⁣
⁣
we men also carry our piece. also conditioned. and we’re coming together to work through them, it is time to do so and we feel your longing too, crying out for us to spiral things up. our call is same as yours: we want to meet you and be fully met by you, just as we are. and simply be. cracked open. once and for all. welcoming all of our parts.⁣
⁣
we want to welcome your strong #masculine, which inspires us to take action and grow into our own masculine. we want our #femenine to be welcomed too, that also reminds you to soften and it’s part of that safety and trust feeling we bring allowing your full openness and surrender.⁣
⁣
we want to welcome our own masculine, penetrative, direct, witness, observer, that also allows your cracking open. we want to welcome your femenine, misterious, unpredictable, expansive, sensitive, expressive, nurturing, that let’s us drop into softening and replenishment, cracking us open too.⁣
⁣
+++ on comments

www.livetothefullest.org

#innerfemenine #metoo #shivashakti #healthyrelating #wearethesame #forgiveness #respect #love #divinemasculine #divinefemenine #iloveyouimsorryiforgiveyouthankyou

text:
the truth is, even for relatively inexperienced hackers, getting access to your webcam isn’t that challenging.

what could a hacker do with this info?
the implications are massive. not only could a hacker abuse your privacy in the creepiest of ways, but they can hold you to ransom and blackmail you based on information they see and hear while watching you over a period of time.

think about it: someone could be watching you walk around in your underpants, or film you getting intimate with your partner. this footage is typically held for ransom. and in some cases, it could also be sold to the highest bidder and used on porn sites. 
parents be aware! 
swipe for some tips on guarding against these hacks...

text:
goodness, i hate sin.
i hate the effects of sin.
of betrayal
dark deceit
manipulation
lies
bullying
cruelty
and abuse.

i hate the levels of pain that i am bearing and there is no remorse.
i hate that  those who offended knew, saw my pain, inflicted and continued in sin in full consciousness that more pain would be added to me and others.
i hate how no one person can truly understand how deep, 
how wide, and utterly destructive this all is, and that bothers me. 
i hate the responses i have received. 
of how many others have been treated similarly by  the same people that call themselves believers. 
that call themselves pastors, churches. 
i hate the belittling, the covering up, the refusal to admit sin. the refusal to listen to me again and again. the discard of me again and again.
i hate the inability to truly care. to say i’m sorry. to be humble.
rather pride is breeding.

i’d be lying if i didn’t admit that there is much hatred that fills my heart toward  the churches that have their hands all over this. folks, he should have never been rehired let alone hired at any church.
walking through this pain, i have come to see seeing how disqualified he and others really are.
and
the pain is deep because it has been disguised behind what appears to be good and right.
behind “gospel centeredness” 
behind “jesus”
behind “the word”

the desire and pursuit of marriage is held way too high as a priority in both churches.
so much so that it has produced such an objectivity to people….. should not be so because they are human beings, with souls, with hearts, with stories. 
they are not objects to means.
from my experience:
the very words of “gospel centered” pastors have been used to objectify women and to lift up the man in pursuit, to fuel control. 
the very words of mentors has been manipulated, used to objectify women and to lift up the man in pursuit, to fuel control.

the reality is that behind what seemed to be good, but was evil. it has been pride and pride and pride. in a spirit of saying we’ve got it all right. [ run from anyone, any church that claims this, has this air]
where the focus has been all on man, the lifting of man, of knowledge.
name: CHELSEY LYNEA

text:
sick in knowing
while discarded
so easily forgotten, 
a lousy confession of abuse, 
a continuation of a hidden affair, 
the blossoms of a new supply, 
suddenly afterwards

an attending of t4g,
a space where his thoughts lifted up, 
a resumption of his control and stance, 
his reputation fed and protected
his sin
his acts
his abuse
enabled, fostered, celebrated
yet i am silenced

to the fooled, to the ones playing in his facade
friends, elders, mentors, pastors, bystanders
"he's the kindest guy we've known"
"he's such a good guy, i approve"

it's as if they say with him
to me
the problem is with you

text:
researchers built a smart dress to show how often women are groped at clubs "for a campaign on behalf of beverage company schweppes, advertising agency ogilvy created a touch-sensitive dress that tracked how often—and with what degree of intensity—women in brazil were groped on an average night out. the goal was to elevate the issue to men, who expressed in preliminary interviews that harassment was not a major issue for club-going women.

for the project, titled “the dress for respect,” researchers built a dress embedded with sensor technology that tracked touch and pressure. the information was then relayed to a visual system so that researchers could essentially track harassment in real time.

to test the dress, researchers sent three women to a party wearing it. throughout the night, we see a heat-map version of it steadily light up in the areas where the women are being grabbed: mostly the lower back, backside, and arms. the visual is imposed over footage of the women brushing off the men and asking not to be touched.

in just under four hours, the women are touched a combined 157 times.

later, men from the party are brought in to review the experiment. for the most part, they express shock and surprise at the now-bruised image of the dress." title: the dress for respect
client: @schweppes
office: @ogilvybrasil @ogilvy

discovered this via @cyclesandsex

#brazil #metoo #timesup #sexualharrassment #clubbing

in just under four hours, the women are touched a combined 157 times.

later, men from the pay are brought in to review the experiment. for the most pa, they express shock and surprise at the now-bruised image of the dress." title: the dress for respect

text: in grad school this was called intergenerational transmission of trauma. science calls it #epigenetics. trauma has the capacity to alter your gene expression...which then gets passed on to your children and to the children of your children, etc🤰🏽🤱🏼👶🏽 trauma carries on a silent “legacy” across generations...you can stop🛑 the legacy of trauma! it starts with a decision “it will stop with me!” 🛑🙅🏽‍♀️ trauma-focused therapy is one of many ways towards healing your legacy. 👉🏼 visit my website to learn more about trauma-focused treatment options. if you interested in reading 🤓 more about epigenetics look up the work of dr. rachel yehuda, researcher in epigenetics and the intergenerational effects of trauma,#spiritual #knowledgeispower #changeyourmindsetchangeyourlife #awakening #wellness #bienestar #ptsd #psychology #metoo #psicologia

text:
you are brave, fearless, bold & strong ✨
.
.
last friday i had the honour of attending a workshop with @birthwellbirthright held by the wonderful @jennfontaine4 via the incredible @penny.simkin on ‘when survivors give birth’ understanding and healing the effects of early abuse and sexual abuse on childbearing women. the numbers are staggering with 1 in every 3 girls will endure sexual abuse by the age of eighteen. many abuse survivors (for very good reason) have issues with control, helplessness, exposure, restraints, trust in their bodies, trust of strangers and authority figures, pain, especially genital pain, penetration of their bodies and discomfort with new situations. anyone involved in any form of care to do with pregnant women, birthing women or care for women in the postpartum period should maybe just assume that a women has in fact endured abuse (whether it has been disclosed or not) and treat her with upmost respect, dignity and patience ... unfortunately it is not a given. 💔
.
.
image from @youmeanddoterra .
.

text:
tarini, award-winning creative director, visual artist, mumbai. .
.
“i am an award-winning creative director by day, and an opinionated visual artist by night. 
my artist name is charaswati. .
i believe in using humor to challenge and dismantle the complexity of being a liberated indian woman in today's day and age. 
art, to me, is an expression and not appreciation. 
my projects live at the heart of my personal ethics, aesthetics, and politics. 
slamming patriarchy with a smile has been my constant endeavor.
.
about the art: i have used the medium of a roach book to voice my opinions about #metoo. 
the roach is the spine of every joint. the medium becomes the art it holds. 
through printed roaches, people consume my art. physical consumption of my belief gives me the greatest high as an artist. 
also, these roach books become pocket bibles of my ideology.”

text: kicking off december 1st with a run and #31daysofsustainableliving. day 1: some weeks, much of my time is spent reading articles and reports about how doomed the planet is if we stick to business as usual (often followed by articles about the ways in which people are stubbornly committed to  business as usual) and during the bad weeks i experience overwhelming climate grief. i have to work hard to remain hopeful and keep my mental health in a good place. one way that i do this is with regular exercise and whenever possible i exercise in nature. my favorite exercise is running. before i became a mom (and before i started working for a cause that i was passionate about) i ran often but it was an aggressive activity. i timed every mile, raced against myself and constantly scolded myself for not running hard or fast enough. thankfully, i’ve now found ways to put my competitive spirit to better use and running is now a joyful time to listen to my favorite songs, reconnect to and thank my body for all the hard work that it does, enjoy endorphins, unclog my brain, allow new creative thoughts to flow, and spend time with my daughter in nature. this running outfit is 50% sustainable. the t shirt is organic cotton from @loomstateofficial but the pants are not.i bought them long before i knew about micro fibers and plastic in clothing. the act of running and the good feelings it engenders are 100% sustainable. my #sustainableliving is imperfect, but always improving.

text:
[out now | booklet 16 pita putih]

25 november adalah hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan internasional dan juga hari pertama 16 hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan, yang merupakan kampanye internasional untuk menghapus kekerasan terhadap perempuan.
———
hal ini dilatarbelakangi oleh sejarah; tanggal tersebut merupakan tanggal dimana 3 mirabal bersaudara dibunuh pada tahun 1960. mereka adalah aktivis yang berjuang melawan kekerasan terhadap perempuan di republik dominika. ———
warna resmi tahun ini adalah oranye. oleh karena itu tagar #orangetheworld muncul, yang mana melambangkan masa depan yang cerah dan bebas dari kekerasan terhadap perempuan. 
di sisi lain, tagar resmi dari kampanye ini adalah #hearmetoo, yang merupakan kelanjutan dari tagar tahun lalu (#metoo) yang memberikan kesempatan bagi penyintas untuk buka suara tentang kekerasan yang dialaminya dan berdiri melawan kekerasan. ———
untuk merayakan hari itu, bidang pemberdayaan perempuan bem fh undip 2018 memutuskan untuk membuat booklet yang berisi informasi umum mengenai kekerasan terhadap perempuan. kamu dapat membacanya di: bit.ly/booklet16pitaputih
kita siap menyuarakan anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan, apakah kamu juga?

#orangetheworld
#hearmetoo

bidang pemberdayaan perempuan
bem fh undip 2018
bermakna, berkarya, bersama!

text:
#genius
a campaign by schweppes sought to prove that men, who expressed in preliminary interviews that harassment was not a major issue for club-going women in #brazil were just flat out wrong.
so they got a touch-sensitive dress designed that tracked how often—and with what degree of intensity—women in brazil were groped on an average night out. "to test the dress, researchers sent three women to a party wearing it. throughout the night, we see a heat-map version of it steadily light up in the areas where the women are being grabbed: mostly the lower back, backside, and arms. the visual is imposed over footage of the women brushing off the men and asking not to be touched.

they were touched more than 40 times...per hour!

watch the experiment via link in our profile.

image via @ipeeyourpants

#forallbodies #cyclesandsex #touch #consent #metoo #emobodiment #embody #nomeansno #consentissexy #dressed #dressy #clubbing #experiment

text:
what are you thinking? it was the question i never liked when i was a young woman, from the boyfriends, lovers, the men around me trying to get into my brain. again and again, what are you thinking? as if they couldn’t bear i had a secret part of me they couldn’t access; they needed to find it out. what are you thinking? if only they knew. because they really didn’t need my honesty. they wouldn’t have liked it, and it would have made my path through the world they’d created for themselves all the more difficult.

what was i thinking? that i hated the sex perhaps. giving blow jobs. that i felt smarter and stronger and more together than the man trying to penetrate my mind, but was never allowed to articulate this and if i did, i’d be punished for it. what are you thinking? that i may well be coolly assessing you, actually. that the man in front of me could penetrate my body but could not penetrate my mind. it was a survival instinct. because i knew that to be loud, abrasive, honest – to tell them what i was really thinking – could cost me jobs and relationships. so i quietened. hid my true self.

what are we thinking? rage. and now we articulate it. last year’s metoo movement was a galvanising moment of insurrection but i fear complacency. fear that we’ll drift back to where we were. because women have always been the butt of hate. from eve, that original transgressor through to the lionesses of the metoo movement, those women who are different, disobedient, audacious, outspoken, will be punished. women pay the price for male insecurity, again and again. our voice is our weapon. deploy it. to lift up those good men who get it, and to shame those who don’t. what are we thinking? guess.

nikki gemmellcolumnist
#metoo #speakout #womenmatter #domesticviolence #whatareyouthinking #speakup

text:
dec 2 // a note she wrote on lemon sorbet // on the second day of christmas my love true love gave to me…there they were, sitting in a love seat, entwined like two turtle doves. she didn’t know whether to be embarrassed and look away or embarrassed and say hello. with either thought her cheeks stung as she sat with her friends trying to enjoy the tea party, while on the other side of the dining room her grandfather sat mooning his paramour, his mistress, his concubine, his slut. she sipped her tea. she took first a sandwich, delicately threaded with salted cucumber, then a scone. as the young girls worked their way up the tiers, they giggled. as thirteen year olds do, she thought. what do they know of the world. of heartbroken women. of loss. such things speak to me and all because of him. that man. i despise him. these were strong words for a flat chested child to think. and as the lemon sorbet arrived, she could take no more. years later she would take great pride in her decision to fold her damask napkin, to place it firmly on her chair before striding out across a room lulled by chinking china, the warmth of pastry and small talk. she remains surprised by the scale of her prepubescent anger. it was the woman who smiled at her first, enquired if all was ok. the girl stood. the grandfather turned. strangely, what hangs in her memory is the neatness, the trim of his moustache. to this day she loathes the prickle. his lip spiking her lowered cheek, an odour of tobacco linking this movement. but she did not straighten, not immediately, she allowed her face to remain close to his and as the twelve year old uttered three small words – i hate you – the man’s jubilance, his mask, dissolved away and this was the beginning of the end. @t2tea 
#t2tea #adventcalendar #christmas #tea #grandfather #lemonsorbet #love #hotelwindsor #families #metoo

text: a very powerful workshop today with @nextgenmen. next gen men is about men confronting, learning and exploring the male gender; the way it is constructed in society, how it plays out in different social structures, and where change begins. in the first picture, jermal discusses effective and ineffective communication regarding conversations about gender and consent. in the second, jonathan discusses the man box, and the constraints it places on men and boys. two awesome exercises, out of many. everyone should be listening to this important organization, that empowers men in a positive way. #socialchange#men#postive#empower#nextgenmen#is#an#awesome#man#feminist#metoo#ally

text:
ah, i love finding the balance of giving and receiving 🙏

so instead of a christmas sale, i will be donating 10% off the original prices to different causes. 10% of the proceeds from this post will go to @riseslo 
rise provides a 24 hour support line, counseling programs, shelter services, and advocacy for sexual assault victims. 
this is a win for the organizations, for the colombian and peruvian families that made the necklaces, and for the person receiving the gift 😍 win-win-win 🙌

let me know if any of the necklaces interest you! i will be excited to be making donations to causes throughout the holidays and beyond 🙏

#indigenousjewelry #colombiannecklace #peruviannecklace #givingseason #beadednecklace #crystalnecklace #metoo #metoomovement #amazonart

text:
"he/she's just not into you." let's think about this statement. who is the 'blame' being deflected onto?

change the language to "he/she's unable to be into you." suddenly, what you knew all along becomes a reality. people carry baggage that they choose to hang onto. no matter what you do, it will never work.

it was never about you.

text:
#throwback ⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣
“the point of maximal danger, is the point of minimal fear” - @willsmith⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣
when i was 19, i was raped by a partner. it’s very rare i actually say that “r” word - it’s easier for me to say assault.⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣
i “allowed” it to happen. i did not fight back. i thought “i’ve been with him already, just let it happen and never see him again. ”⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣
what i didn’t realize was by not standing up for myself, speaking for myself, using my voice and “letting it happen” - i did myself a major disservice. ⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣
using my intuition to avoid and prevent...being vocal. using my skills to create distance. overriding my freeze response and overriding my excuses of “its ok, you just won’t hang with him again now that you know this will happen.” ⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣
i called my friend that night crying and telling her what happened. i felt pathetic. how could a defense instructor not acknowledge or defend her assault? that was hard for me. i didn’t speak about it otherwise.⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣
that ex never thought he did anything wrong (except for the fact i started posting about consent on my timeline and he would become extremely angry with me for discussing those topics - duhhh. i hope he internally knows he did wrong)⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣
i knew i had to make my personal development a priority. i started listening to podcasts every day. i hardcore dropped negatives (people + events) in my life that never assisted by growth. i woke up earlier. i fed myself better. i tried to love more. ⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣
i choose to rise. i choose resilience. ⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣
now, i push myself. i go to live  seminars. i invest a lot in my self-care and self-growth. i invested in amazing coaches to push me forward and hold me accountable.⁣⁣⁣
.⁣⁣⁣
help me create a culture of consent⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣
download my free “self defense strategies” cheat sheet to unlock your intuition and soulful spirit. #linkinbio⁣⁣
⁣⁣
name: Arielle K👊🏽Defense Strategiest

text: i had a full weekend planned: i’ve got almost a dozen survivor stories to transcribe, even more leaves to finish painting, the online submission form to complete, emails to respond to, more art supplies to purchase- and i woke up this morning barely able to move. i’m feverish, the room is spinning, and i can’t get much further than a few feet from the bathroom for safety’s sake. for the first hour or so, i tried to push through it and convince myself i wasn’t sick. “i’ve got so much to do! i’ve gotta stick to the plan! right??” but- of course- that didn’t work. i had to stop and do nothing. and as i’ve been convalescing today, i’ve been thinking about how often i force myself to do more than i can handle. how often i’ve sacrificed my health- physical and mental- for productivity’s sake. how we’re conditioned to only stop when we really have no choice but to stop. i’ve been feeling so guilty for not getting anything done today, and not knowing whether i’ll get anything done tomorrow. so this is a reminder to myself and anyone who needs it to be unapologetic with you selfcare. take the time you need to check in with yourself and recharge when you need to. you won’t be much help to yourself or anyone else if you don’t! ✨🌱 #putyourmaskonfirst #sickday #selfcare #dayoff #selfcaresaturday #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #workinprogress #artist #monstera #watercolor #survivor #survivoradvocate #survivorselfcare #metoo #believesurvivors #believewomen #believeblackwomen

text:
глен клоус, лејди гага, кетрин хан, никол кидман, реџина кинг и рејчел вајс се шесте познати дами кои ја красат насловната на последното издание на the hollywood reporter.
облечени во фантастични црвени креации, во интервјуто за магазинот тие говорат за движењето #metoo, за тоа колку е различен холивуд денеска и посочуваат дека има нешто силно и во тоа да си ранлив.за сликањето, актерките се договориле дека овојпат ниту една нема да носи панталони и мора да признаете дека секоја една од нив изгледа совршено во внимателно одбраните дизајнерски парчиња.
речиси секоја една од актерките кои се наоѓаат на насловната, имале проблем со некој од нивните колеги без разлика дали биле актери или пак некој од екипата и биле дел од непријатна ситуација или нешто посериозно.

text:
i got to work with two amazing women tonight who reminded me about owning your truth. when you are not living a life that is serving you or honoring you, a life that in not in alignment with your best interests, there are consequences. you can become so detached from your emotions that you have difficulty feeling anything or you can exhaust yourself trying so hard to suppress them that you can barely breath. i have such gratitude for these incredible women for being brave enough and honest enough to admit that they were struggling. there is such power in owning your truth. once you do, you have the power to change. .
.
.
.
.

text:
sorry ari, i respect the message but can’t get behind that thank you. the second part i’m all about though. 💁🏼‍♀️
.
some people do not deserve your gratitude and that’s okay. you can still unburden yourself of anger and resentment, you can still move forward, you can still heal from the pain and trauma they caused you, and you can still come to peace with your experience without absolving your abuser of guilt for their offenses. don’t let anyone tell you otherwise.
.
forgiveness is a personal decision. do as you wish. but know that you don’t have to forgive or thank an abusive ex or any sociopath in your life for anything. some things are just unforgivable. and while you can be grateful for the lessons learned, you have your intuition, your insight, your strength, and your courage to thank for that, not them.
.
so that’ll be a “no thank u, next” from me. ✌🏻💛🦋

some people do not deserve your gratitude and that’s okay. you can still unburden yourself of anger and resentment, you can still move forward, you can still heal from the pain and trauma they caused you, and you can still come to peace with your experience without absolving your abuser of guilt for their offenses. don’t let anyone tell you otherwise.
.
forgiveness is a personal decision. do as you wish. but know that you don’t have to forgive or thank an abusive ex or any sociopath in your life for anything. some things are just unforgivable. and while you can be grateful for the lessons learned, you have your intuition, your insight, your strength, and your courage to thank for that, not them.
.
so that’ll be a “no thank u, next” from me. ✌🏻💛🦋

text_retweet:
world aids day! 
#repost @warif_ng (@get_repost)
・・・
day 7 | december 01
world aids day

during sexual assault that involves  penetrative sex, women are exposed to infections as perpetrators do not typically use any forms of contraception such as condoms. this leads to a higher incidence of hiv/aids cases.

if untested, women run the risk of spreading this infection to others and if untreated, can lead to death.

the use of post- exposure prophylaxis (p.e.p) treatment of hiv with the appropriate drugs within 72 hours of the assault reduces the risk of infection.  this treatment is available at the warif centre - free of charge.

if you are a survivor of sexual violence or rape, visit the warif centre or a medical facility within 72 hours to get tested and treated, to reduce your risk of the hiv /aids infection.

warif cares. world aids day

⏺ at the end of each day i thank god for my family, and then i try to find one good thing that happened that day, and i thank god again. and i close my eyes knowing that through the son of god - indeed god made man, born into history - i know that in the end, all will be made right. for everyone. .
luke 21:25-28, 34-36
.
25"and there will be signs in sun and moon and stars, and upon the earth distress of nations in perplexity at the roaring of the sea and the waves, 26men fainting with fear and with foreboding of what is coming on the world; for the powers of the heavens will be shaken.27and then they will see the son of man coming in a cloud with power and great glory.28now when these things begin to take place, look up and raise your heads, because your redemption is drawing near." 34"but take heed to yourselves lest your hearts be weighed down with dissipation and drunkenness and cares of this life, and that day come upon you suddenly like a snare;35for it will come upon all who dwell upon the face of the whole earth.36but watch at all times, praying that you may have strength to escape all these things that will take place, and to stand before the son of man."
.

text: la calle estaba llena de gente. sobre todo a las puertas del local. gente de unos cuarenta o cincuenta, al igual que el loco cabrón acosador. en un segundo caminó rápidamente varios pasos hasta ponerse a mi lado mientras gritaba lo que gritaba. yo no fui consciente hasta segundos después y, primero el desconcierto, luego la rabia, me invadieron. enseguida me dejó tranquila porque alguien le llamó "¡luiiiiis! incluso puede que fuera borracho o drogado. me da igual. la cuestión es cómo alguien puede hacer y decir lo que él hizo y dijo. al contárselo a mi novio más tarde me dijo que le daba mucho asco, y rabia también porque él nunca lo presencia. eso es: lo hacen cuando vamos solas. #indignacion #acoso #metoo #feminismo #machismo #abuso

did you know that in the usa, 3 women die every single day, and a woman is beaten every 12 seconds due to domestic violence. also, the a high percentage of children who live with domestic violence in their homes, grow up to do the same. the cycle of violence runs deep.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
my ex-husband had been terribly abused as a child. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
i broke the cycle for my children. it was the hardest thing that i ever had to do. being a survivor has altered every molecule and minute of my life. today helping others recover from abuse is what i am called to do. rebel thriver welcomes all of the survivors out there to join us. you can learn to find your voice if you haven't already. there is a way through the pain that you may be in. here you can get advice, be educated, supported, and loved (link to email in bio). knowing that someone else understands the kinda crazy that you live with in your head is priceless. it is possible to live a thriving life. you just have to believe. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
how wonderful is it to find people who make you laugh, smile and feel good? social connections are vital 🌿 but it can be hard for some teachers to make that time for themselves after having people connections all week. having people you can trust, people you can talk to and people who will support you is fundamental for a teacher. peer support is an area i have been exploring that other professions use as a strategy to maintain the wellbeing of their people. at an emotional intelligence workshop we were told - if you don’t have a best friend get one, and, it’s more important who you eat with than what you eat. interesting provocations to consider.
it can be as simple as calling a friend • dropping in to visit someone • teaming up for a walk • having a coffee date • meeting for a meal ......
and on that note i am heading off to make plans with my soul people 💜  artwork: @loriportka  #healthyteacher teacherselfcare #teachersofinstagram #teacherhealth #healthyteacher #teacherwellbeing #teachersfollowteachers #teacherssupportteachers #onlyateacherknows #teachersupport #overwhelmedteacher #stressedteacher #mindfulnessteacher #findyourtribe

text: i’m at a loss for words as to how i’m going to narrate this story. as i lay back and relax at noo and omid’s i’m literally recharging my batteries. the comforts of a warm bed, hot shower and their hospitality are what i need right now. but a few days prior i had a completely different recharge. as i camped out in the wilderness with little to no modern comforts my mind and soul were recharged. an african safari that i struggle to put into words. i’m so grateful for life right now that it’s overflowing. a wide spectrum of emotions that i know i have to take the time to give it justice. can’t wait to share this with the world! #keepgoingandgoing

text:
the "snowglobe" has become extremely  symbolic to me. on february 2, 2016 i suffered a traumatic brain injury due to a domestic violence assault.
my neurologist explained my injury to me in this way..."the damage to your brain shook your white matter loose and white matter doesn't reattach it just settles back down." as she said that she used her fingers to display something like rain falling to the ground.  my reply to her was this..."so now, i have a big snowglobe for a brain?" she kind of giggled, said that's a fun way to look at it, but yes.... i am a fighter, a survivor, a fucking warrior 
#iamthefaceofbraininjury #tbiaffectedme #tbisurvivor #tbiwarrior #tbiawareness #domesticviolencesurivor #metoo #icare #breakthesilence #irishamerican #irish #narcissiticabusesurvivor #irishgirl #badassempath #empathwarrior #warriorwoman #warriorsoul #empath #warriorspirit #woundedhealer
#tbianniversary 2/2/16

this is a photo, of my siblings and my confirmation, in april 1979. we were born in  may 1962, october 1963 and may 1965 but we all confirmed, the same day. 
what is not pictured in here, is the "brazeness" of #childrapists #childmolesters #childabusers #sexualpredators and #sexualdeviant roaming #trinidad and #tobago. the person who took that family photo (which is the only photo, that exists of my some of siblings, my father and me), was #cecilgomez the #peteacher at #curepejuniorsecondary, who had been screwing, my sister, when she was 12 y/o. she was 15 y/o here. there he is, in the presence of our father, a man - twice his size, at a sacred ceremony, for the daughter - he had molested. by this time, she was too old for him and he had solicited me. fortunately, i had enough sense, to know what he was about and stayed away, from him. 
my sister doesn't remember, who took this photo. i don't remember, why he attended, the confirmation as he was catholic and we were anglicans. did he show up, as a visitor, to witness our confirmation or did he have someone else there and happened - to be around, to snap a photo!? i'm thinking it was the latter but that is something. the child #molesters are too often, a trusted member of society and a family friend or neighbor, who is supposedly above reproach, while they use their position, to prey on the vulnerable. #despicablepeople.

text:
today i had a seizure. .
i feel like failed myself. .
i am in a fog.
.
even writing these words is difficult. .
my seizures are physicalolical reaction to extreme anxiety.  aka a form of panic atrack.
.
this month is #consistencydecember. and here is where the #brightside come in.
.
my #silverlining is because of all personal growth i have achieved i didn't resort giving up. in fact i went okay what can i do to relax and shut down for a few hours. what can i do after that low stress but will still let me stay constant. .
last seizure took weeks to mentally recover from. .
that is what consistency in working on my personal development has achieved. .
#hopeful #seizuressuck  #progress #itwillbeok #isurvived #metoo #ptsdmom  #mentalhealthwarrior  #mentalhealthwin #iamme

text:
‘never assume her silence is consent’ ~ @thesarahdoughty

yes, #metoo
this is kind of a hard topic to talk about and i have tried to banish these memories to the very end of my memory. i tried to hide them in a corner, hoping i would never find them again. 
but i know that, if i want to make peace with my past, that i have to face and accept what has happened.
when i was 16 years old, i was sexually harassed by my trainer. i never said a thing, i didn’t scream or try to defend myself. i was paralysed, felt myself numb and i couldn’t believe this was happening to me.
so i remained silent, for days, months and eventually years. it’s still difficult to talk or write about this, because it brings out feelings of anger, anxiety and disgust.
but i can tell you that there doesn’t go a day by where i don’t think about what has happened. why he had done that and how he could do that. i was 16, he was +/- 48. 
this happened, but this never should have happened. so darling, please, don’t keep such a things for yourself and scream whenever somebody does something to you what you don’t want. protect yourself.

my silence was not my consent.
———————————————————
{ #metoo #metoomovement #stopsexualharassment #selfcare #selflove #sportphotography #photography #sports }

text:
1, 2 or 3?  which one is the right one? 😏 #swipeleft👈 .
.
.
look people, we’re not here to tell you that there’s only one way to skin a cat 🐈. (setting aside the fact that there are many types of cats to begin with 🐅🐯🦁🐱🐆)
.
same goes for industries and businesses - too many to count. so, of course there are countless methods for branding yourself or your business properly. we’re not here to tell you that #thejagformula is the only #rightway to do it. that would be foolish. (although it definitely works 😏)
.
however! ☝️🤓 there are certainly surefire ways to #doitwrong and that’s what this post is about. it’s about deciding whether or not you can afford to spend the next few years, months, weeks or even days promoting or publicizing your brand incorrectly as opposed to doing it #rightfromthestart.
.
can you afford to be experimenting with your #brandingandmarketing? if you get it wrong, how will you know? better yet, when will you know? what will be your indicator that it’s time to adapt? #evolvewithus
.
here @jagbranding & @jagbrandingec 🍌 we put an emphasis on laying the groundwork early on with our clients to adapt the #mindset of spending the time and money to do things right from the get. what that means is we follow a process and control as many of the variables as possible while tracking your results and acting on the insights driven from the #data . 📊
.
here is our basic #checklist for executing multiple campaigns on multiple platforms for multiple clients in multiple industries...#successfully:
.
1️⃣ establish the goals
2️⃣ customize the strategy
3️⃣ adapt & evolve as needed
4️⃣ work in phases
5️⃣ stick to the plan
.
wanna do it right the first time? #dontdoityourself ...that’s #rulenumber1 .
ready to dive in with a pro? contact @jagbranding today : click link in bio ☝🏼☝🏼☝🏼

on estime que 39 millions d'enfants américains ont été victimes de violences sexuelles aujourd'hui.

84% des détenus ont été victimes de violence dans leur enfance.

les enfants sont souvent victimes de violence de la part de ceux en qui ils ont confiance. 30 à 40% des victimes sont victimes de violence familiale. 50% de plus sont victimes de violence de la part de quelqu'un en dehors de la famille, qu'ils connaissent et en qui ils ont confiance. environ 40% des enfants plus âgés qu'ils connaissent sont victimes de violence.

la violence sexuelle se produit non seulement avec les adolescents, mais aussi avec les jeunes enfants

laura freixas (el país) "¿qué hacemos con ‘lolita’
de vladimir nabokov? 
quienes defienden lolita, ¿lo hacen porque es una obra de arte y a pesar de que muestra, e implícitamente justifica, la violación de una niña, la reducción del ser humano femenino a la condición de objeto para el placer masculino, la ridiculización y burla de cualquier mujer no sometida... o lo hacen porque su condición de obra de arte la sacraliza y nos prohíbe por lo tanto criticar todo lo anterior? (como piensa lola lópez mondéjar: véase cada noche, cada noche,su interesante novela-ensayo sobre lolita). por cierto, quizá no está de más recordar (es este otro detalle en el que los defensores de lolita raramente reparan) que el mundo está lleno no solo de humberts, sino de lolitas: de niñas y mujeres maltratadas y violadas. que esto preocupe solamente al 1,8 % de los españoles algo tendrá que ver con una cultura, de la que lolita no es más que un ejemplo, que banaliza esa violencia. y que del 1,8 hayamos pasado en unos meses al 4,6 % (última encuesta del cis), algo tendrá que ver a su vez con la campaña #metoo.
(...)
retomo la pregunta del título: ¿qué hacemos con lolita? a la luz de lo que llevo dicho, se comprenderá mi conclusión: leerla, sí, porque es una gran novela. pero también analizarla. criticarla. usarla para entender cómo el patriarcado manipula en su beneficio, y para nuestra desgracia, la cultura. buscarle alternativas: leer y dar a leer otros textos, que en vez de reproducir ad nauseam la visión patriarcal del mundo, nos ofrezcan un nuevo punto de vista, como hace frida kahlo. cualquier cosa, en fin, menos sacralizarla.
name: María A.M. Ruiz de la Peña

laura freixas (el país) "¿qué hacemos con ‘lolita’
de vladimir nabokov? 
quienes defienden lolita, ¿lo hacen porque es una obra de arte y a pesar de que muestra, e implícitamente justifica, la violación de una niña, la reducción del ser humano femenino a la condición de objeto para el placer masculino, la ridiculización y burla de cualquier mujer no sometida... o lo hacen porque su condición de obra de arte la sacraliza y nos prohíbe por lo tanto criticar todo lo anterior? (como piensa lola lópez mondéjar: véase cada noche, cada noche,su interesante novela-ensayo sobre lolita). por cierto, quizá no está de más recordar (es este otro detalle en el que los defensores de lolita raramente reparan) que el mundo está lleno no solo de humberts, sino de lolitas: de niñas y mujeres maltratadas y violadas. que esto preocupe solamente al 1,8 % de los españoles algo tendrá que ver con una cultura, de la que lolita no es más que un ejemplo, que banaliza esa violencia. y que del 1,8 hayamos pasado en unos meses al 4,6 % (última encuesta del cis), algo tendrá que ver a su vez con la campaña #metoo.
(...)
retomo la pregunta del título: ¿qué hacemos con lolita? a la luz de lo que llevo dicho, se comprenderá mi conclusión: leerla, sí, porque es una gran novela. pero también analizarla. criticarla. usarla para entender cómo el patriarcado manipula en su beneficio, y para nuestra desgracia, la cultura. buscarle alternativas: leer y dar a leer otros textos, que en vez de reproducir ad nauseam la visión patriarcal del mundo, nos ofrezcan un nuevo punto de vista, como hace frida kahlo. cualquier cosa, en fin, menos sacralizarla.

text:
i’m about half-way through dare to lead (from @brenebrown) — listening on @audible and reading when i can. ⁣
⁣
it’s an amazing resource and i’ve pulled many quotes, insights, and areas i want to further explore with myself into a notebook. ⁣
⁣
today, the above is resonating with me — she uses the #metoo movement as an example of how owning our story, versus denying, ignoring or rationalizing it away, can bring power and growth. ⁣
⁣
what part of your story do you need to own? ⁣
⁣
how can you make the tough aspects of your life part of the foundation to grow upon? ⁣
⁣
